So the length depends on where you enter the chain. 27 enters at 82, which is before 41. So it gets the full length of the 41-chain plus the steps to get to 82. 127 enters at 287, which is after 41. So it gets a shorter length.

To find the next record-setter, I need a number that enters the long chain as early as possible, or enters a new, even longer chain. 73 entered at 83, which is after 41? No, 73 went to 83, then 250, 125, 376, 188, 94, 47. 47 is in the 41-chain. So 73 entered at 47. 47 is further down the chain than 41. But 73’s path to 47 was long. 73 to 47 is 12 steps. And 47 to 1 is 104 steps. So $12+104=116$.

27’s path to 41 is 2 steps ($27 \to 82 \to 41$). And 41 to 1 is 109 steps. So $2+109=111$.

So 73 is longer because its approach to the 41-chain is longer, even though it enters later. It’s like taking a longer road to a highway.

